Module 1: Fundamental concept

 

1.1.        Create new project

To start working on I2G, users need to create a new project as the first step.

All of input data, processed data and interpreted results will be saved in the project.

-       Step 1: In the Data tab, click New project (1). Input the project information.

-       Step 2: Click OK (2). A new project will appear in the project (Figure 1.1).

Figure 1.1

 

1.2.        Import Data

1.2.1 Import las file in project.

Importing Las files comprises two steps:

                  -  Import to Inventory Explorer: The files will be loaded and patched into Inventory Explorer and ready to be shared for different projects in the later step.

                  -  Import from Inventory to project

a. Import to Inventory Explorer

    -    Step 1: In the Data tab, click Import, and select Inventory Explorer (Figure 1.2.1.1).

Figure 1.2.1.1

-       Step 2: In the Inventory Explorer window, select Import LAS (Figure 1.2.1.2).

Figure 1.2.1.2

-       Step 3: Select one or multiple Las files, Click Open (Figure 1.2.1.3).

Figure 1.2.1.3

 

     The wells will be imported into Inventory Explorer (Figure 1.2.1.4).

Figure 1.2.1.4

b. Import from Inventory to project

    -  Step 1: Click Import in the Data tab, select Import from Inventory (Figure 1.2.1.5)

Figure 1.2.1.5

   -  Step 2: Select the wells from inventory, put them the Import Queue by clicking(4), and click(5) to import queuing wells in Import Queue window into the Project (Figure 1.2.1.6)

Figure 1.2.1.6

 

                  Tips:

-       Inventory Explorer is the storage for loaded data in the project browser.

-       In the Import Queue, users can uncheck the curves or wells to be loaded into the project by clicking on those wells or curves and click  . Users can erase all the selected log curves by clicking  on Import Queue curve

-       In this version, core data only is loaded in Las 3 format. Other data can be loaded in both Las 2 and Las 3 formats.

-       Use button Refresh inventory    to reload if the newly imported data hasn’t shown up

-       Use button Toggle well name/file name    to change from well name to file name and back again.

         Import a continuous dataset file split into 2 sections (similar to import Las file):

                  - Import from computer to Inventory Explorer

                  - Import from Inventory to Project

a. Import from computer to Inventory Explorer

   -      Step 1: In the Data tab, click Import select Inventory Explorer (Figure 1.2.2.1).

Figure 1.2.2.1

-       Step 2: In the Inventory Explorer window select Import CSV (Figure 1.2.2.2).

                  

Figure 1.2.2.2

 

-       Step 3: Users can use “drag and drop” CSV file from computer or click on Drop/Click to upload to select the file from window browser (Figure 1.2.2.3). Then click Open (Figure 1.2.2.4).

 

     

 Figure 1.2.2.3

Figure 1.2.2.4

-       Step 4: User has to define a data file structure by selecting the line number containing (Figure 1.2.2.5):

•       Set the header line (mandatory)

•       Set unit line

•       Set data line (mandatory)

Confirm by choosing Next.

   

Figure 1.2.2.5

 

                  Tips:

-       Users can choose a number of lines to be shown in the preview window. 50 lines from the top of the file will be set as default.

-       There are 2 ways to set those lines: (1) Enter a number into the box or (2) pick directly on the data line

 

 

-       Step 5: In the CSV-Wizard window, Click Load (4). Data will be uploaded onto Inventory Explorer (Figure 1.2.2.6)

Figure 1.2.2.6

 

 

Note:

•       Well name and data set name will be automatically defined based on the original file names

•       Null will be defined as -9999.

•       The first column will be automatically set as Reference Column.

•       Depending on file types, the position of the depth column may be various. Therefore, users need to manually correct it.

•       It is not necessary to define the curve columns, I2G will identify them automatically.

 

b. Import from inventory to Project

-  Step 1: In the Data tab, click on Import, select Import From Inventory (Figure 1.2.2.7). Appears the Import From Inventory window

-       In the Import Queue window, if users want to remove the curve(s)/well(s), select them and choose     to remove the selected curves. To remove all items in the Import Queue, select    (Figure 1.2.2.9)

         Since CSV is the free-style format, the software will not recognize all variables by each column. It required to convert them to the basic format of the reference-curves. The following steps guide you through the process:

-       Step 1: In the Home tab (1) on the menu bar, select CSV transformer (2). (Figure 1.2.3.1)

Figure 1.2.3.1

-       Step 2: Drag-and-drop to-be-converted CSV file from the computer into the window or select Drop/Click to upload files (3) (Figure 1.2.3.2), a button to select the file from window browser. Then click Open (4) (Figure 1.2.3.3). After uploaded, the file will be listed.

Figure 1.2.3.2

 

Figure 1.2.3.3

 

-       Step 3: For each listed file, the user can modify its properties by selecting the Setting button (5) (Figure 1.2.3.4) to open the Setting dialog box.

 

Figure 1.2.3.4

 

-       Step 4: In the Setting Dialog, define the data file structure by selecting the line number containing:

§  Set the header line (mandatory)

§  Set unit line

§  Set data first line (mandatory)

•       Confirm by choosing Next (6) (Figure 1.2.3.5)

Figure 1.2.3.5

                  Tips:

-       Users can choose a number of the line to be shown in Preview window. 100 lines from the top of the file will be set as default.

-       There are 2 ways to set those lines: (1) Enter a number into the box or (2) pick directly on the data line.

 

-       Step 5: In the next dialog, depending on loaded data, Well and Dataset columns need to be defined by right-clicking the top cell of target columns. Select OK (7) (Figure 1.2.3.6)

Figure 1.2.3.6

-       Step 6: Click Convert (8) in the CSV transformer window (Figure 1.2.3.7).

 

Figure 1.2.3.7

 

-       Step 7: When the file has been converted, click on the Download (9) to download the file to the user’s computer (Figure 1.2.3.8). The downloaded file can be loaded into the Project at chapter “Import a CSV into Project”.

Figure 1.2.3.8

                  Tips:

-       When loading multiple files, users can apply settings for all files by clicking

-       Click    to remove files

-       Allows users to edit unit

 

1.2.4     Import Image

  An Image log track can be created in a Log-plot as follow:

-       Step 1: On log-plot, right-click on Add Image Track (1). The Image Track Properties pop-up window will appear.

-       Step 2: In this Pop-up window, the user can define:

•       Show title checkbox: toggle show/hide track title.

•       Top justification

•       Track background: Select background color for the track.

•       Width(s)

•       Width unit

•       Zoom factor: Displaying core images along with log changes the vertical factor of a track adds value to display the core image track with a different zoom factor.

-       Confirm the setting by selecting OK (2). An Image Track will be added to the current Log-plot.

Figure 1.2.4.1

        After an image log track is created, there will be two methods to add image data into it.

q Method 1:

•       Step 1: Right click on the Image track and select Add Image. (Figure 1.2.4.2)

•       Step 2: Define the Start (depth), End (depth) by hold & drag the left-mouse to create image interval. The Image Properties window will open right after the interval being created. (Figure 1.2.4.3)

 

                           

Figure 1.2.4.2                                        Figure 1.2.4.3

-  Step 3:

§  Choose select to input the image file from the computer. Select upload to send the image directly into I2G then OK to confirm (Figure 2.3.4).

§  The uploaded image will be displayed on the Image track for the selected interval (Figure 2.3.5).

                               Figure 1.2.4.4                                 Figure 1.2.4.5

q Method 2:

-       Step 1: Open Image track properties pop-up window by double-click the Image track or right-click on it and select track properties. (Figure 1.2.4.6)

-       Step 2: Select Add (1) to create a new row to add and define an image. Click on Image (2) to open the Image properties pop-up window. (Figure 1.2.4.7)

                          Figure 1.2.4.6                         Figure 1.2.4.7

-       Step 3: Choose Select (3) and then Upload (4) to load and send the images to the user’s i2G Project.

-       Step 4: Manually input the Start (depth), End (depth) (5), then OK (6) to confirm and close the Image Properties window.

-       Step 5: When the Image Track Properties window automatically reappear, the newly added Image’s information will be updated in its column. Select OK (7) to confirm. The uploaded image will be displayed on the Image track for the selected interval.

                   Figure 1.2.4.8                                             Figure 1.2.4.9   

                  Tips:

-       The user can display the image in Image Track at 1:1 ratio by ticking the Smart Display checkbox in the Image properties window.

-       Right click on an image and select Show Image to view the image at original size.

-       To remove an image, right-click on it, select Remove Image option or press Delete keyboard

Note:

-       Uploaded images are stored in gallery of i2G

1.3      Data Editor

-       A tool for displaying digital or statistical data. It allows you to edit the data value and shows the statistics of each log and filters the desired zones.

-       The Data Editor    locates at the Data processing tab.

-       There are two methods to open the Data Editor tool.

Method 1:

-       Step 1: Click on the Data Editor ().

-       Step 2: Drag and drop curves from the Data-Tree into the Data editor window (Figure 1.3.1)

 

Figure 1.3.1

 

Method 2:

-       Step 1: Choose curve(s) on the Data tree.

 

-       Step 2: Right-click on the selected curve(s). Choose the Data Editor (Figure 3.2). The Data Editor window will appear.

Hint:

•       You can select multiple log curves by holding Shift/Ctrl while selecting.

 

Figure 1.3.2

 

1.3.1 Visualization modes: There are 2 modes:

-       Data

-       Statistic

a.    Data mode

-       Display log curve values at each depth point

-       The user can highlight data by zone on data board

-       Data can be edit manually by select cell and type new value in or by pasting a table from Excel or other file types.

-       Data can be copy from the board directly to excel sheet (Figure 1.3.3)

-       Edited log curve can be saved by Right-click on it and select Save as new

-       To overwrite an existing one, click Save Curve(s) button

 

Figure 1.3.3

 

 

   Tips: users can modify the displayed number precision according to the value format (it modifies the number of decimals)

- The user can create new curves here by selecting Add Curve (  ) (Figure 1.3.4), Add New Curve pop-up window will appear, input the curve information and select OK. New curve will be created and listed in the Data Editor window (Figure 1.3.5).

Figure 1.3.4

  

Figure 1.3.5

Tips: Users can go to a particular line by pressing Ctrl+G shortcut key. A pop-up window opens according to the Depth (D) or Index (I) setting.

 

b. Statistic

-       Display curve information (number of unique values, standard deviation, mean value...(Figure 1.3.6)

1.5      Basic concepts of task

 

q Task:

 

     In i2G, a task is referred to a package of a calculation procedure to convert input curve(s) into desired G&G information. The user can create more than one Task and then link them together in a WorkFlow for a total customized by the user.

Figure 1.5.1

These tasks can easily be accessed in the Petrophysics tab ribbon

Learning Objectives

   After completing this Best Practice, the user will know how to:

•       Manually create a Task.

•       Input curve into a Task.

•       Run the calculation.

•       Add the result to a Flow.

•       Working with Flow

      Since the structure of every task is identical, in this Best Practice we will only go through Gamma Ray task as an example (Figure 1.5.2).

-       Step 1: Select the Petrophysics tab (1) ribbon and navigate to Clastic section.

-       Step 2: Select Shale volume => Gamma Ray (2)

Figure 1.5.2

 

 

There are 4 main tabs in a task including (Figure 1.5.3):

1.    General

2.    Input Configuration

3.    Output Configuration

4.    Input Selection

 

Figure 1.5.3

1.    General tab:

-       Task name: Edit box to set the name for this task. A default name will be put here. User can modify it.

 

-       Save option:

·      Output curves: only output curves into a data tree after run task

·      Output curves and log-plot result: output curves and log-plot into data tree after run task

2.    Input Configuration

         The purpose of this window is to select the mnemonic (Family group, Family, or Curves) to be used in the method.

It includes 4 section (Figure 1.5.4):

-       Data type filter selection buttons.

-       Available mnemonic list with options to filter by well and search

-       Default parameter value table

-       Required input selection list

 

Figure 1.5.4

      The Data type filter has 3 levels to be selected and will determine what the mnemonic type will be displayed in the available mnemonic list.

-         Family group contains families that indicate similar G&G properties. (Figure 1.5.5).

Figure 1.5.5

-        Each Family contains log curve that has similar logging purpose. (Figure 1.5.6)

Figure 1.5.6

-        Curve: Individual log curve in all the dataset of all the selected Filter wells (Figure 1.5.7).

 

Figure 1.5.7

 

 

                                                                                                                                                     Tips: Family Group is the best option during this stage as it will be more flexible for users to select Input curve later.

     By default, i2G will self-select input data considered to be consistent with the methodology of a Task.

User can manually re-assign a different mnemonic by:

1.    Selecting it in the available mnemonic list

2.     Click on the desired input combo box (Figure 1.5.8)

 

Figure 1.5.8

q Filter Wells:

 

-       The Filter allows one or multiple wells to be selected.

 

-       The available mnemonic list will display mnemonics that are available in at least one filter well (Figure 1.5.9).

 

Figure 1.5.9

q Default Parameter value table:

•       Allows the users to edit certain setting parameters and methods of the task (Figure 1.5.10).

 

Figure 1.5.10

 

Note:

       - Initially, a set of default value will be automatically input for all the Parameters.

3. Output Configuration tab:

     This tab includes: Curve name, Family and Unit

(Figure 1.5.11):

     

Figure 1.5.11

q Curves Name:

-       Define output curve(s)’s name.

-       A typical curve name associated with the selected mnemonic will be generated as default.

-       User can edit.

q Family:

-       Define the family for the output curve(s)

-       In this example, it is Shale Volume (Figure 1.5.12).

Figure 1.5.12

q Unit:

-       Allows the users to edit Unit in the drop-box.

-       All the available Unit for the defined family will be listed for user selection (Figure 1.5.13).

Figure 1.5.13

 

4. Input Selection tab:

-       Inputs sub-tab/ table (Figure 1.5.14):

·      The table includes Well, Output Dataset, and Curve columns.

·      Select well to run the task on by drag-and-drop desired well from data tree.

·      The first dataset will be selected as default destination in output data set, the user can manually re-select other in the drop box next to well name by double-click on it.

2.2.         Zone set Manager

-       A zone set is a specific dataset storing your zones of interest as intervals/a collection of one or many zones in different intervals.

-       Each zone is defined by its information (top and bottom depth) and its template.

-       A zone set template specifies the display properties of a zone set.

-       A Zone set template is a collection of one or many zone templates. Each zone template contains the zone’s information such as name, background, foreground, and pattern.

-       Zone set ó Zone set Template, Zone ó Zone Template.

-       Zone set and zone set template are jointly managed by Zone set manager form. (Figure 2.2.1)

Figure 2.2.1

Figure 2.2.2

-       When modifying any property, the software will automatically update accordingly.

           To create a new Zone set Template (Figure 2.2.3):

1.    From the Template Set tab, click icon (1) and then type your Zone set template name >> OK (1).

2.    After created the Zone set Template, the select icon     on the right hand-side of Template Set tab to create a new Zone Template (2).

3.2 Marker Manager

 

-       Markers are used to mark the geological changes of rock along the depth of an underground well.

 

-       A marker set is a collection of multiple markers.

 

 

-       The structure of each marker consists of marker depth and marker template.

 

-       The marker template specifies the display part of the marker including name, color, line width, and line style (Figure 3.2.1 a&b)

 

Figure 3.2.1 a

Figure 3.2.1 b

To open Marker Manager form:

From menu bar (1) >> Select Data tab then click on Marker Set Manager(2) >> The Marker Manager form (3) will be displayed (Figure 3.2.2).

Figure 3.2.2

 

a. Template Set tab:

-       The Template Set tab is the determinant of the displaying properties of the marker as well as the marker set. A marker template contains information fields including name, color, line width, and line style. Template settings will be managed in the Templates tab of Zoneset Manager form (3).

-       From the Template Set tab, you can change every displaying property of each marker. When applying changes on the name, color, and line style of the marker template, the software will automatically update the marker(s) using that marker template.

      To create a Marker set Template (Figure 3.2.3):

1.    In the Template Set tab, select icon    (1). The New Template form will appear, input marker set template name > OK

2.    After creating Marker set template, click on      icon at the right corner of the tab to create a new marker template (2).

4.    Click icon      to save the Marker set template (3).

 

   

Figure 3.2.3

b. Marker Set tab

-       The Marker Set tab helps the user manage the data of the Marker set of all available well in the Project (4) (Figure 3.2.4).

-       The Marker name and Marker Set name and other Marker’s properties are assigned by corresponding Marker template.

-       To load a marker set to the form on the right-hand-side, Select the well and the marker set.

Figure 3.2.4

 

To add Marker:

1.    Click on icon     on the right side of the form (1). The Create new Marker form will display (2) (Figure 3.2.5 and 3.2.6).

Figure 3.2.5

Figure 3.2.6

-       At the right side, the depth shift table gives information about depth position of every single point. It includes depth position of origin and shifted. You can manually enter a depth value, the shift point on logplot will be updated automatically (Figure 7.3.1).

9.2.3 Model Parameters – Multiperceptron

       Multi Perceptron is a class of feedforward artificial neural network. An MLP consists of three types of layers of nodes, including an input layer, hidden layers, and an output layer. Except for the input nodes, each node is a neuron that uses a nonlinear activation function. MLP can be used for both classification and regression problems. The supervised learning technique utilized for MLP is the backpropagation algorithm (Figure 9.2.3.1).

Figure 9.2.3.1

Input parameters

Input parameters for this model are defined as follows:

Activation: is the name of activation function for hidden nodes (Figure 9.2.3.1).

·      ‘logistic’, the logistic sigmoid function, returns f(x) = 1 / (1 + exp(-x)).

·      ‘tanh’, the hyperbolic tan function, returns f(x) = tanh(x).

·      ‘relu’, the rectified linear unit function, returns f(x) = max(0, x), Maximum Iteration: is the maximum number of iterations. Unless the training model converges at some point during the training process, which is determined by “Tol” parameter, it will stop when the number of iterations exceeds Max_iter.

Figure 9.2.3.2

-       Tol: Tolerance for the optimization. When the loss or score is not improving by at least for two consecutive iterations, convergence is considered to be reached and training stops.

-       Initial Learning Rate: It controls the step-size in updating the weights.

Figure 9.2.3.3

                  Tips: Advanced parameters that can be adjusted in case the normal ones are not capable of generating the desired output

Network Structure

-       The user can design their model architecture by typing the number of hidden layers (“Hidden_layer_sizes”) and the number of nodes in a layer (“layer 0”/”layer 1”) depending on how complex their data are.

-       The model architecture is visualized by the window on the right and is automatically updated when changed.

-       When the user wants to eliminate any input nodes (curves): click on the node

Figure 9.2.3.4

9.3.2 Model Parameters

 

-       7 learning algorithms are offered in this module, including 1-Decision Tree, 2- KNN, 3-Logistic Regression, 4-Random Forest, 5- Neural Net, 6-Self Organizing Map (SOM) and 7-HIMFA

Figure 9.3.2.1

Neuranetclassifier (Figure 9.3.2.2):

-       NeuraNetClassifier is a multilayer perceptron network for classification problem. This model optimizes the log-loss function using LBFGS or stochastic gradient descent. Input parameters for this model are defined as follows.

-       Activation: is the name of activation function for hidden layers.

-       Algorithm: is the name of training algorithm, which is either a backpropagation or evolution strategy algorithm.

-       Backpropagation algorithm works best with many epochs.

-       Evolution algorithm is preferable with a smaller number of epochs, about 1000.

-       Batch_size: Number of samples per gradient update. If batch_size =0, the number of training samples will be used.

-       Learning_rate: It controls the step-size in updating the weights.

-       Num_epochs: maximum number of training iterations.

-       Optimizer: is the solver for weight optimization.

-       Warm up: is to determine the initial values of weights. When set to True, the model will run with batch_size = 1 and num_epochs = 1 to get the initial weights, otherwise, it just randomizes the initial weights. After this process, the model will run the training process as set by other parameters.

-       Boosting_ops: this parameter is only used for the evolution algorithm. This parameter determines the number of times that the weights are further updated based on the accuracy after the training process based on the loss function finishes. The default is 100.

-       Sigma: this parameter is only used for the evolution algorithm. This parameter determines the variance size of the Gaussian distribution used for randomizing the weights.

-       Population: is the number of sets of randomized weights for each epoch. This parameter is only used for the evolution algorithm.

 

Figure 9.3.2.2

Module 10: Summation Task

10.1  Summation and Report

       Based on user-defined cut-offs, the Summation algorithm determines the reservoir intervals, quality, and thickness.

Learning Objective  

•       After completing this module, you will know how to use the Summation algorithm for reservoirs.

10.2  Summation Interface

 

•       Click  Summaries  in the Petrophysics menu to open the Clastic-Summaries task window (Figure 10.2.1)

 

Figure 10.2.1

 

10.3  Sumation Interface

There are three dedicated mandatory inputs: Shale Volume, Porosity, and Water Saturation.

-       Be aware that these are used as cut-off values.

      Reference for Summation

-       The Summation algorithm can be simultaneously launched using several references (MD, TVD, TVDSS) if available in the selected dataset. By default, the algorithm uses the MD as the reference of selected dataset.

 

 

Output Configure tab allows cut-off curve selection for defining the output flags.

By default, ROCK, RES, and PAY are associated with the Shale Volume, Porosity, and Water Saturation curves (Figure 10.3.1).

-       ROCK: Defines the shale-free depth intervals. By default, only the shale volume cut-off is active.

-       RES: Defines the potential reservoir intervals in the ROCK’s intervals. By default, the shale volume and the porosity cut-offs are active.

-       PAY: Defines the hydrocarbon impregnated reservoir intervals. By default, the shale volume, porosity, and water saturation are taken into account.

 

Figure 10.3.1

Input Select tab, the user can drag and drop multiple wells which are defined as a summary. Users can summarize by zone or by well (Figure 10.3.2).

Figure 10.3.2

In the Parameters section (Figure 10.3.3), you establish the cut-offs for each curve. By default, each curve has a predefined range. In this case, Shale Volume, Porosity, and Water Saturation curves have a predefined range between 0 and 1.

If additional curves/families are used, the limits of their display range are extracted from their family databases and can be manually modified.

The bounds can be modified in the predefined drop-down list. By default, the range is between the minimum and maximum cut-off values including the actual minimum value:

Minimum cut-off <= Range of values < Maximum cut-off

And is written as: min <= val < max in the Parameters tab.

Figure 10.3.3

10.4  Summation Tab

       Each of the Summation tabs (Summation MD, Summation TVD, Summation TVDSS) summarizes these measurements:

 

 

 

 

 

Attribute

Description

Gross

Thickness of the zone.

Net

Thickness of the interval defined by the cut-off values and the different flags that were used in the analysis.

Net To Gross

Ratio of net-to-gross.

BVW

Bulk volume of water. Equation: BVW = net

average porosity * average water saturation.

Porosity thickness. Equation: POR-TH = net

Hydrocarbon * Porosity thickness for each selected zone.
